The day I decided to quit in-person training…

During my transition from in-person training to online, there was a lot of self-doubt and uncertainty.

The money from in-person training felt safe. Although not always consistent, it was safe.

The problem was, I wanted more for myself.

I know opening a gym was not an option because it would conflict with how I wanted to live my life.

Which was to create geographical freedom for myself. 

I wanted the option to get up and go as I pleased and work from wherever I wanted.

A life in-person training couldn't provide. The only way to achieve this was to take my fitness business online.

I remember waking up on a summer morning in 2019 with sheer frustration. 

I threw the bed sheets off of me, walked over to the bathroom mirror, and looked myself in the eye.

And I promised myself to be done with in-person training by the end of 2020!

Fast forward 3 months later, I created my online fitness business, @fastshredz, which would become a six-figure online fitness business by the end of 2020. 

and have continued to generate multi-six figures years later.

But it wasn't the money I was after. That came with it. 

It was the utter desire for geographical freedom and to have more control over my time and income.

For any trainer that's looking to get into online coaching, I want you to look past the money (even though money is important), But think about the type of life you want to live. This is where the motivation will come from.

If you're an in-person trainer looking to learn how to take your fitness business online, I created a free mini-course showing you how.

If you want access to it, DM me the word "REMOTE", and I'll send it to you.

Trainers looking to take their fitness business online. Making the transition can seem daunting, but with the right approach, it can be a success.

When some prospects express a preference for in-person training, it's often because they lack knowledge of the benefits of online training.

As the trainer, it's your job to educate and inform them that online training may be the best solution for reaching their fitness goals. 🤔

Instead of simply telling them about the benefits of online training, try asking them questions such as:

▫️ "Why do you feel you need an in-person trainer?" 

▫️ "Do you plan on having a personal trainer for the rest of your life?" 

▫️ "What happens when you travel? Will you take a personal trainer with you?"

These questions can help clients realize that in-person training may be a short-term solution, but learning to train themselves is a long-term one. 👍

When pitching your online program, highlight the personalized workout plan, custom nutrition plan, progress tracking, and community of like-minded individuals all working towards their own fitness goals.

💻 Emphasize the convenience of having everything at their fingertips, whether they're at home or on the go.📱

Not only will your clients benefit from online training, but as a trainer, you will also have more time to focus on growing and scaling your business, as well as taking on more clients.📈. 

And the best part, you can train your clients from anywhere, as long as you have a laptop and internet connection

In summary, when a prospect expresses a desire for in-person training, use it as an opportunity to educate them on the benefits of online training and how it can help them reach their goal.🏋️‍♀️

The truth is, you can’t be an out-of-shape trainer and expect to be successful. 

It’s like a chef who doesn’t eat their own food, or a mechanic who drives a broken-down car. It just doesn’t make sense.

That’s why I always made time to work out, no matter what.

When your clients see that you practice what you preach, they respect you more and are more likely to follow your advice.

Think about it, if you were looking for a personal trainer, would you want someone who is out of shape and doesn’t seem to care about their own health?

Of course not!

You want someone who is fit, healthy, and passionate about what they do. 

Being in great shape also helped me attract more clients and charge more for my services.

People are willing to pay more for a trainer who has proven results and looks the part.

When I decided to transition my personal training business online, I knew I had to bring that same mindset with me.

I made sure to continue prioritizing my own fitness and health, even as I worked to build my online presence.

And you know what? It paid off in a big way.

Being in great shape made it easier for people to trust me and see me as an authority figure in the industry.

When potential clients saw my own progress and transformation, they were more likely to believe that I could help them achieve their own goals.

And because I had already established myself as a successful personal trainer offline, I was able to use that reputation to my advantage to building a six-figure online fitness business.

A big part of that success was due to the fact that I was able to earn people’s trust and establish myself as an expert in the industry.

So if you’re thinking about transitioning your own fitness business online, I can’t stress enough how important it is to bring that same mindset with you.

When you lead by example and practice what you preach, people will naturally be drawn to you and want to work with you.

DROP A “💯” If YOU AGREE

5 key components to focus on to get your clients to hit that ‘renew’ button again and again.

1️⃣ Custom Programs: One size never fits all in fitness. Customize your programs to suit each client’s unique needs and goals. Clients are more likely to follow a program made specially for them that aligns with their goals and lifestyle. 

2️⃣ Regular Check-Ins: Communication is key! Regular check-ins show you care, and you’re right there with them every step of their journey. I like to do weekly check-ins and monthly program updates.

3️⃣ Celebrate Their Wins: Celebrating Every milestone, big or small, keeps your clients motivated. Make sure to have a process to collect your client’s progress photos.

4️⃣ Educate Your Clients: Knowledge is power! The more your clients understand the ‘whys’ and ‘hows’ of their journey, the more invested they become in the process. Teach them, don’t just tell them.

5️⃣ Build a Community: Create a space where your clients can share their struggles, victories, and everything in between. When clients feel like part of a tribe, they’re more likely to stick around.

6️⃣ Real-Time Changes: Regularly ask your clients what’s working for them. What’s not? Be ready to switch things up if something isn’t working.

Remember, getting clients is just the start; keeping them is where your business truly grows. 🚀
